ERTS WAS NOTIFIED THAT A TRIMAC CTMV WAS INVOLVED IN A MULTI VEHICLE ACCIDENT AS THE RESULT OF A PASSENGER VEHICLE HYDROPLANING ON WET ROADS AND IMPACTING WITH THE CMTV UNIT WHICH THEN RESULTED IN A ROLLOVER. Unit 1, a truck tractor semi trailer (intermodal container) went off of the road on US 20 westbound approximately 1/2 mile west of Dameier Rd.  The combination rolled into the ditch on the north side of the roadway.  The ditch was lined with large rocks that led to a small creek with flowing water.  The container, loaded with 20,635 kg of Sodium Hydroxide, was detached from the trailer chassis. The container  box was damaged and product released into the ditch. Damage was  Approximately 10 bags of material released outside of the container.  The product was reactive to water and rain was forecasted.  A hazardous material team from Stephenson county arrived and began loading the released product into barrels and put a large tarp over the material that could not be collected between the rocks.  The container was loaded onto a low boy trailer and relocated to a large garage to avoid the rain.

Transport shipment was a mixed load types and containers of hazardous waste from one TSDF destined for another.  Driver noticed the leak during a stop at the address provided.  Driver reported leak through the Rineco Emergency Response Hotline.  Rineco's ER director immediately took steps to notify local, state and Federal agencies as required.  The Polk county sheriff department was called first to help control the scene do to the nature of chemical hazards present on the trailer.  The ER director then notified our nearest contract ER response team USES out of Deer Park Tx to mobilize.  Reporting to the NRC was completed as well as the TCEQ spill hotline: TCEQ report number 20152512.  Response proceeded smoothly with the help of the county law enforcement and fire.  Fire department covered liquid with oil dry absorbent until the contract responder arrived and made entry to trailer.  Drum was identified as the culprit and the response information and chemcial makeup was given to the onsite responders by Rineco ER director.  Drum look to have been punctured at some point by a nail.  Since this is a waste shipment it came from another original shipper.  The drum on the Rineco trailer was loaded directly on the floor of the trailer which is metal.  Appears that maybe the drum was nearly punctured before and finally gave away on the shipment to the next consignee.  All material was contained and overpacked or packed and removed from the incident with oversight of the Texas Department of Environmental Quality Rep onsite in response to the report to the state.
column169: The response as is went as well as one could.  The inspection of containers including the bottom of drums received full is difficult but we strive to inspect containers for shipping worthiness before they come to our facility but as the waste exemption allows in 49CFR they are often reused containers.

column168: A Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. box truck containing hazardous waste arrived at the Clean Harbors' Clackamas, OR 10 day transfer facility to consolidate LTL waste onto a van trailer to be shipped to the final waste disposal facility. Facility personnel noticed that one of the two cubic yard containers was leaking during the off load process. An internal response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the truck and unloaded the leaking cubic yard container. The leaking cubic yard container and the second manifested container were repackaged into drums for continued transportation to the final disposal facility. The box truck floor was cleaned with a cleaning compound and returned to service. All released waste and the associated cleaning materials were packaged for disposal. The release was reported to the Oregon Department of Environmental Quality. Operator 'Keelyn' provided report # 2015-1575.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or breakage was observed. This release was the direct result of improper container inspection, selection and preparation. The driver will be retrained on proper container inspection and selection for solid and liquid waste streams. The shipper has been advised of free liquids being present in a solid waste stream and that all future shipments must not contain free liquids. Future shipments containing free liquids will be rejected for transportation.

column168: The UTLX 130509 was found to be leaking while in Barstow yard receiving track #10. The acid on the car and ballast were neutralized.

column168: I, John Vergis, Environmental Officer for the Wheeling and Lake Erie was called at 1634 hrs on July 15, 2015 for car DBUX 303194 that was suspected to be leaking a a strong vapor.  When I arrived at 1700 hrs., I investigated and realized the the vacuum relief device was leaking vapor at a fast rate.  The vapor was exhausting from the car instead of being drawn in to it.  I could not get the valve to stop leaking.  I called Chemtrec to report the incident at 1747 hrs.  The car owner contacted me and gave me permission to call in a contractor to remove the device and plug it temporarily.  The leak was stopped and as of July 22, the car is sitting in Brewster awaiting a permanent repair so in can move to destination to be offloaded.

On July 1, 2015, at 23:51 hours the Blount County Communication Center reported a tank car on fire CSX Mile Post 00C 290.62.  CSX personnel responded and found that the south bound Train S 54101 had derailed and de-trucked the A-end of tank car UTLX 901717, a loaded tank car of Acrylonitrile, Stabilized.  Damage incurred during the derailment included cracks to the AR and AL lower portions of the tank shell; this damage resulted in product release and a subsequent fire.  The shipper, INEOS USA LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC Report 2015-0702-00010.  Once the car was empty and the fire had been extinguished the breached tank car was removed from the railroad, clean and purged, and secured pending any further investigation.

Summit Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the frangible disc in the non-reclosing pressure relief device had ruptured. column168: On July 14, 2015 at 06:05 hours, personnel at CSXT Avon Yard reported NATX 304041, a loaded UN 1170, Ethyl Alcohol tank car to have derailed from the track within the Avon, Indiana Yard which resulted in a release from the manway area. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Grain Processing Corp. was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2015-07-14-00045. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Summit Environmental Contracting, the Indianapolis, IN branch office was dispatched to the scene. Upon arrival the tank car was discovered on its side with a slow leak coming from the manway.  Upon further investigation it was determined the manway gasket had deteriorated to a point in which there was a quarter inch gap at one section of the gasket.  The manway was contained and the car was repositioned onto its wheels which stopped the leak.      A HAZMATHOLD was placed on NATX 304041 and will require a transfer of the commodity before being released.      Cause Code: 209 at 5 points  NARRI: 5 (5 + 3 + 0) x (2 + 0) = 80

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: I, John Vergis, was contacted by the Wheeling and Lake Erie Train Dispatcher about a car that was reported leaking by a passing train in our Siding in Bridgeport, Ohio.  When I arrived and located the leaking car CTCX 780266, I noticed that ice had formed on the outside of the protective housing.  When I opened the lid, I noticed that the liquid valve on the B end of the car was leaking liquid.  I tried to tighten the valve but the leak would not stop.  I checked the plug in the end of the valve and found that it was less than hand tight.  I tightened the plug and the leak stopped.  I checked the plugs in the vapor valve and the liquid valve on the A end and found that they were less than hand tight also so I tightened those as well.  I waited to make sure the leak would not resurface and then resealed the car.
column169: Better car securement procedures are needed.

column168: During transit, driver inspected his load at a break stop, and discovered that the IBC was leaking at the 21" dome closure on the top of the IBC. A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the temporary storage phase, facility personned noticed liquid material leaking from the bottom of a van trailer.  Facility personnel obtained the shipping document and profile information for the material loaded on the van trailer and determined that deploying granular absorbant in conjunction with spill boom was the appropriate immediate measure to contain the spread of the release.  Once containment had been secured internal notifications were made and facility personnel assembled a response team. First stage of full response was to use containment / spill trays under the leaking are to prevent additional material from hitting the ground.  Decontamination and clean up were concluded and all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into suitable packages. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.  Upon conclusion of the cleanup the compromised container was inspected and it was observed that bolts securing the outlet valve body to the flange on the container were not sufficiently tight resulting in a slow leak.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. IN addition,the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required  specifications.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: During offloading operations, a refrigerated gas dewar cylinder was observed off-gassing from a pressure relief valve in the rear of a trailer. The trailer was isolated to the parking lot and allowed to off gas as designed. After 2 hours of off gasing, the pressure relief valve did not close. An environmental contractor was dispatched and determined the pressure in the cylinder was well below the pressure relief valve setting and was still off gassing due to an apparent failure of the pressure relief valve. The cylinder was isolated to a remote area of the parking lot and the supply valve was opened allowing the contents of the cylinder to be released entirely. No wastes were generated from this incident. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted by the release. The empty cylinder will be staged at the terminal pending the shipper's disposition.

column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Defective Component or Device
column168: The driver of this vehicle traveled only 1.5 miles from his previous stop when he discovered the spill.   His 48' trailer had four skids of nonhazardous cargo in the nose and a 55 gallon drum of corrosive lqiuid strapped to the wall of the trailer in the last eight feet of the trailer.   Some time during the 1.5 mile trip from his previous stop, his pallet jack broke loose traveled approximately 30 feet in this trailer.   The pallet jack crashed in to the very bottom of the steel drum causing a puncture and and a release of corrosive liquid.  The driver was not aware of any release until he opened the door at the Frank Edmonds Company.  When his trailer was opened a significant amount of the corrosive liquid poured out the back door on to the surface below the dock door he was parked in.   Approximately 30-40 gallons of this corrosive liquid was vacumned out of the sewer located right below his trailer tires.  Spill Center was contacted and a remediation contractor was dispatched to the scene. The trailer was wiped clean, the punctured drum was over packed, and the release in the sewer was vacumned and placed in a drum for hazardous waste disposal.
column169: Notices are being placed at all our driver locations warning all drivers to immediately replace any defective pallet jack straps.  The cause of this spill was failure on the part of the driver to use a proper functioning pallet jack strap.  Had he done so, his pallet jack would have stayed in place and this release would not have occurred.

column168: Tank car UTLX65621 containing sodium hydroxide solution was struck by tank car RCRX2177 as it came off the hump at Norris Yard.  The coupler on RCRX2177 struck the head of tank car UTLX65621 causing a dent and crack.  The incident caused the spilling of approximately 600 gallons of sodium hydroxide solution.  The remainder of the load was transferred to another tank car or captured in a spill containment pool and recovered by a vacuum truck.  The incident occurred as the result of a power failure in the area which prevented the retarders on the hump from properly slowing RCRX2177.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: During unloading activities, it was discovered that one 1-5 gallon plastic pail of UN3109 organic peroxide had been punctured by a protruding pallet nail. Onsite personnel over packed the damaged drum into a metal drum and continued it with shipment. The UN3109 reacted with the metal drum resulting in the approximate release of 2 liquid cups to the trailer floor and pavement below. A contractor responded, neutralized the release, and over packed all impacted material into a poly drum. No drains, soils, or waterways were impacted.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: During a routine walk through inspection at the Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. in-transit 10 -day storage facility at Lake Point, UT a leaking drum was discovered. The drum was discovered to have a pin hole leak on the bottom surface area resulting in a release of material. Facility management was notified and an in house crew responded. The response crew donned the proper PPE, over-packed the damaged drum and clean up debris into a suitable salvage drum, and secured the drum for continued transportation to the intended disposal facility. The Utah Department of Environmental Quality was notified. UDEQ operator Niel Taylor provided report #12281.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation no evidence of leaking was observed. The pin hole in the drum appeard to be the result of corrosion on the interior of the drum's bottom surface. The shipper was advised of the incident and was requested to inspect all drums in current inventory for any containers with suspect integrity. The driver was re-instructed to perform a thorough inspection of all containers prior to accepting them for transportation and to reject any containers with suspect integrity.

column168: At 09:18 hours on July 6, 2015 a report from the general public was received that AMOX 33858, a residue Liquefied Petroleum Gas tank car, was leaking from the top of the car as it passed through Norco, LA.  KCS Environmental + Hazmat dispatched a response contractor to investigate.    Upon investigation, ice was discovered around the "B" End Liquid Line Valve secondary closure plug.  An inspection of the "B" End Liquid Line Valve revealed that the valve was not closed.  It took a full turn and a half of the valve wheel to secure the valve to a fully closed position.  The "B" End Liquid Line Valve and the secondary closure plug was found to be less than tool tight.  Additional deficiencies were noted.  The "A" End Liquid Line Valve secondary closure plug was less than tool tight.      File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: A Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. driver discovered a leaking drum in transit from the shipper to the designated disposal facility. The driver immediately notified management and an in house response team was mobilized to the scene. The response team donned the proper PPE, located the leaking drum in the trailer, and over packed the drum into an approved salvage container. The drum was then transported to the original disposal facility without further incident. The Nebrask Department of Environmental Quality was notified. Operator Jim Borovich provided report #073115-jb-1220.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the drums for transportation no evidence of leaking was observed. An internal investigation revealed that the container failed for two reasons.  1) The container closure was not tightly closed.  2) The container was not properly secured against movement in all directions which allowed the container to tip over in transit. The driver has been retrained to conduct a thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take the appropriate actions. Additionally, the driver was retrained in proper load securemnet. This release was the result of human error and the driver will be internally disciplined per company policy TC2.1 Disciplinary Guidelines.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the staging phase, it was discovered liquid material leaking from the van trailer and into containment.  Facility personnel obtained the shipping document and profile information for the material loaded and determined that deploying granular absorbant in conjunction with spill boom was the appropriate immediate measure to contain the spread of the release.  The failed container was identified and removed from the van trailer.  Visual inspection of the container showed the contents were leaking from the area where the valve attached to the bottle.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. Follow up investigation with the generating customer revealed that they had been provided a number of 275 gallon portable tanks with incompatible valves for the content.  Additionally the generating customer indicated they had had similar failures at their location.  Generating customer provided assurance that all suspect 275 gallon portable tote tanks have now been removed from service.     Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity.

column168: While unloading a van trailer containing various hazardous waste shipments at the intermediate truck transfer facility, a wet pallet was found.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the drum, which had a small leak at the bottom seam.  The trailer floor was cleaned with a suitable cleaning compund which was also placed into the salvage drum. column168: The SK van trailer was staged at the Lexington, SC facility.  The driver was conducting a walk around of the trailer when he noticed material leaking out the back of the trailer.  The driver immediately applies sorbent material on the spill.  He then made notification to plant personnel which responded to the spill.  The van trailer doors were opened by the response team and the damaged drum was located towards the back of the trailer.  The drum had a small puncture on the bottom of the drum.  The response team over packed the drum and the material that was cleaned up both on the ground and inside the trailer, was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: The drum was not leaking prior to being loaded on the van trailer, but while in transit a leaked developed. At this time there are no recommendations.

This was due to absolutely no packing material inside the box (padding / absorbent, etc.)  Pictures to be provided.  The cans are clearly markued " Paint, Un1263 Packing Group III". The accompanying documents do not show anything in regards to hazardous paint. Only notations on the bill are in regards to batteries traveling as "Not Restricted" under special provisions.
column169: This information will be passed on to Head of our Dangerous Goods Dept. for further internal investigation.

column168: The shipping facility transfers the material from a rail car into our tank wagon using nitrogen pressure. When the loading process is completed, the facility uses nitrogen to clear the hoses. When they did this material splashed up into the crash box and ran out the overflow tubes where it was captured in large drip pans
column169: In the future the facility will adjust the nitrogen pressure to eliminate the potential for a release of material.

column25: South Carolina Electric & Gas V.C. Summer Station
column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, LOW SPECIFIC ACTIVITY (LSA-I) NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: A shipment of radioactive material was received as shipment number 15-0457 on July 22, 2015 at Alaron Nuclear Services located in Wampum, PA from the V.C. Summer Nuclear Station (shipment number 15-027).  The shipment consisted of two small metal containers (shipped as UN2912 Radioactive Material, low specific activity (LSA-1)) and one large metal "seavan" container (shipped as UN2913 Radioactive Material, surface contaminated objects (SCO-II)) of waste metal on a flatbed trailer carried by Landstar.  Upon radiological surveillance during receipt and offloading, it was discovered that the sealand container exhibited removable beta-gamma radioactive contamination below the right side door up to 4,000 dpm/100cm^2 and that the trailer had an approximately 16 ft^2 area near the front of where the sealand container was that exhibited removable beta-gamma radioactive contamination up to 4,000 dpm/100cm^2 and fixed beta-gamma radioactive contamination up to 67,000 dpm/100cm^2.  The container and trailer were quarantined in a controlled area of the Alaron facility, the container was decontaminated, and V.C. Summer personnel were notified.  V.C Summer personnel performed an investigation at the Alaron facility the following day after which the trailer was decontaminated and released back to the carrier. The container was kept at the Alaron facility.  Preliminary investigation indicated that failure of the lid gasket seal due to warping caused by misalignment of the ratchet tie downs may have allowed infiltration of the environment and accumulation of water that escaped the container under the front door.
column169: Carrier should retrain drivers on the proper use of ratchet tie downs when securing a shipment as to not damage the cargo.
column172: General packaging, for type A radioactive materials

column168: Tank car GATX 57978 was reported to be releasing product from the top of the car while in motion.  The car was set-out and secured for the evening.  Inspection on July 8, 2015, found two of six manway swing bolts in position but less than tool tight and one of six manway swing bolts not in its proper position.  The manway gasket was inspected and appeared to be in good condition but it was removed and replaced by a gasket fashioned from expanded Gore-Tex rope.  The manway cover was resecured and the car released to continue in transportation.  No remediation was needed as the product evaporated prior to reaching the ground.
column169: Ensure cars are properly secured prior to release from the plant and movement in transportation.

column168: ERTS was contacted concerning a release of approximately 1 ounce of UN1210 printing Ink inside trailer. The release was inside a box containing 4 smaller boxes and not on any other surface. The release was caused by the box pushing against nails protruding on the pallet. The box was already dry with a stain when Con-way terminal personnel entered the trailer. Terminal personnel were directed by ERTS to over pack the box into an appropriately sized drum, using the proper PPE because the box was dry. There were no drains, soils, or waterways impacted by the release. There were no road closures, no evacuations, and no injuries caused by the incident. A DOT5800 is required due to the packing group designation of PGII. There were no RQs met or exceeded. There is no other regulatory reporting required at this time.

column168: ERTS was contacted concerning a 55 gallon release of UN1760 Sodium Hydroxide from a 55 gallon drum onto the dock. The release was caused by a forklift driver puncturing the drum on the bottom. There were no drains, waterways or soils impacted by this release. there were no road closures, no evacuations, and no injuries caused by this release. A DOT 5800 is required due to the packing group designation of PGII. The RQ for sodium hydroxide is 1000 lbs. There is 9 lbs per gallon. 9 X 55 gallons = 495 lbs. The RQ has not been met or exceeded. There is no other regulatory reporting required at this time.

column168: A Clean Harbors driver arrived at the customer site to pick up a load of drums containing hazardous waste.  When the driver staged his trailer at the loading dock a customer representative advised the driver to stay in the tractor and to give the tractor keys to the representative. The customer loaded the trailer and then brought the keys and the paperwork to the driver. The driver reviewed the paperwork, sign the manifest and then moved the trailer forward to check and secure the load. The driver did not see any liquid on the floor of the trailer. The driver departed the customer site and as he was enroute to the destination facility a OH State Trooper pulled the driver over and notified him that something was leaking out the back of his trailer. The driver opened the doors and noticed that the trailer floor was wet. The driver placed a 5gal pail in the front corner of the trailer to catch any additional material that was leaking from the trailer. The local fire dept responded and dispersed speedi-dri to the contaminated area on the ground. Clean Harbors response team responded and found a 55gal steel drum with 2 puncture holes 3/4 way up on the drum. The drum was immediately overpacked and the the spilled material was cleaned up and released for transportation to the intended disposal facility.
column169: Conducted meeting with customer to require drivers be present at the loading dock when van trailer's are being loaded at the customer site.  This will allow the driver to inspect the drums integrity prior to being loaded.

column168: At 0830 ERTS was contacted in regards to a UN1263, Class 3, PG II, paint release. During the unloading process, Con-Way personnel found one (1)- five (5) gallon pail that was leaking due to the handle being ripped off during transit. Approximately 1/2 gallons of the paint was released to the trailer floor. It is unknown the cause of the handle being torn off during transit. Con-Way personnel had already cleaned up the release at the time of the call. Con-way personnel used absorbents to clean up the release and placed the damaged pail into a 55 gallon drum and placed it in their OS&D.
PUC conducted inspection and found release from top of car. Inspection of the car by response contractor found all six manway swingbolts were less than tool tight, resulting in release.

column168: NATX 300802 had a vapor release from the manway. The gasket was misaligned and pinched. The gasket was removed and replaced with a temporary Teflon gasket.

column168: TM Russell Fraser called SID to report possible Hydrochloric Acid release from rail car UCLX 30060. Rail car shows in TSS to be an empty residue car that last contained Hydrochloric Acid. Release occurred in the Newton Yard in track 8108 during switching operations with Y-NEW1022-16A. Estimated amount of released product is less than 2 gallons along the side of the rail car. No injuries reported or waterways impacted. BNSF Environmental Mgr. James Farner was notified and advised Hazmat Response would handle cleanup.  Hazmat Response identified the release as coming from the Liquid Line.  Occidental Chemical mobilized a crew to replace missing nuts/bolts on the liquid line and secure for transport.
column169: Shipper (Consignee) should identify and review procedures with personnel for securement of tank cars prior to departing from facility.

column168: TM Brian Featherston called SID to report less than one (1) ounce of Fuel Additive released from rail car UTLX 645916 in the La Mirada Yard on track 6334. The release was caused by a loose bolt on the bottom valve handle. No injuries were reported or waterways impacted. BNSF Environmental Mgr. James Farner was notified and advised local BNSF Hazmat responder already handled incident.  BNSF Responder tightened the loose bottom outlet valve packing retainer and secured the release.
column169: Identify and Review procedures with loading personnel for securing of tank cars and inspection/documentation to ensure tank cars are secured prior to offering.

column168: FRA Hazmat inspector Randy Boyington identified UTLX 204321 as possibly releasing due to a strong ethanol odor when walking near the car.  After inspection of the man way, two of the man way nuts/bolts were found to be less than tool tight.  The car was set out on Track 6022 for repair.  NRC responded and confirmed the release of vapor only due to loose man way bolts # 1 + 6.  The man way was secured and the vapor release was secured and confirmed by air monitoring.
column169: Shipper shall identify and review securement procedures with personnel unloading tank cars.  Shipper had identified that the man way is usually not a procedure for offloading and stated in this case it was opened and required for a calculation of product.

column168: At approximately 18:05 (CST) on 7/16/15 the U-TNDAWA0-10 train derailed at MP 167.24 while travelling at approximately 44 mph.  The cause of this is still under investigation.  As a result of the derailment 22 tank cars containing petroleum crude oil derailed.  The STAX 10808 was punctured and lost a portion of the contents to soil.  The puncture was approximately 5" x 5" on the side of the tank car.  The spill was contained by natural barriers on-site and free liquids were vacuumed and recovered for later disposal.  The release was stopped when the car was rolled with the hole above the liquid level (approx. 10:00 7/17).   Cleanup for the crude oil in soil remains underway including excavation, product recovery and remediation.    At approximately 18:05 (CST) on 7/16/15 the U-TNDAWA0-10 train derailed at MP 167.24 while travelling at approximately 44 mph.  The cause of this is still under investigation. column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: On 07/20/15, the OOLU 31636 was reported LEAKING by the assigned driver prior to outgate, at BNSF Los Angeles. The waybill listed the cargo as HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (Class 9 / UN 3082 / Marine Pollutant / LongChain Alkyamine). Twenty gallons had leaked onto the ground in Lot 3, Row 9. In the interest of safety, the unit was moved to the Containment Pit and United Pumping Services was dispatched to address the incident. A total of (20) gallons leaked from a 55 gallon drum at the rear of the container; upper layer. The cause of the leak was determined to be Drum Failure. A small hole was discovered between the lower and upper chime. The drums did not appear to have shifted during transit.  Drum was overpacked, cargo unit was cleaned and proceeded to deliver.
column169: Inspect packages prior to loading to determine suitability.  Carefully manage loading process to ensure proper securement and no potential punctures due to sharp objects during the loading process or during transit.

column168: Tank car NATX 303562 was reported emanating vapors in the railyard.  The responder reported vapor source was at NATX 303562's vacuum relief valve (VRV).  The faulty VRV was removed and a threaded pipe plug was secured in the vacated VRV orifice which ended any further vapor release.  The VRV appeared to have a faulty "o" ring.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve
column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: At approximately 1917 CT a BNSF yard employee in the Tacoma, WA terminal observed tank car TILX 194849 to be leaking from the bottom outlet valve.  The employee noticed that the BOV handle was not pinned in the closed position.  Employee closed and pinned valve handle and observed the car to see if the leak would stop.  With the leak stopped the terminal spotted the car to a track where BNSF hazmat responders could evaluate the car.  Responders found the bottom outlet cap/plug to be less than tool tight.  They were able to secure the cap/plug with a wrench to achieve secondary closure.  Less than one gallon was estimated to be released, gravel spots where product touched the ground were remediated with a shovel.  Car was released back into service.
column169: Shipper needs to ensure valve handles are closed and pinned for transportation as well as any outlet caps/closures/plugs are wrench tight per DOT standards.  Should review loading and pre-trip process with loading employees, re-train as necessary, and audit for compliance.

column25: Great Northern Gathering + Marketing by Great Northern Midstream LLC
column168: A BNSF train stopped on the main track was reported with entrained tank car CBTX 740354 leaking commodity from its top fitting area.  BNSF responders were able to stop the commodity release from CBTX 740354's liquid valve.  Inspection revealed that liquid had by-passed the closed liquid valve and the TODO 4 inch high flow self-sealing coupling system applied on to the liquid valve.  CBTX 740354 isolated in the rail yard is awaiting replacement liquid valve that has been ordered and after the new valve is installed contractor is scheduled to perform a leakage pressure test. column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: There was a release of approximately 3 lbs of battery acid from a fork lift battery caused when the battery fell over in transit. The release impacted the trailer and also the dock. There were no drains, waterways, or soils impacted by the release. There were no road closures, no evacuations, and no injuries caused by this release. The contractor neutralized the acid to a pH of 8 on the dock and over packed it into a drums.

Our driver made a right turn into the front of another truck that approached on his right in the blind spot. Delivery tubes were broken causing the fuel inside them to leak onto the cement. Our clean-up crew responded by using absorbent pads, kitty-litter, microblaze, more absorbant, then quick-crete powder. Then they blew off the excess powder not absorbed into the cement from brushing it. The diesel leaked out for around 4-5 minutes.
column169: We continue to stress a safe driving culture throughout the company with a strict adherence to current safe driving habits and programs.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: Local train crew reported an odor emitting from car while being switched. Inspection of car by local environmental contractor dispatched by the shipper, revealed four of eight manway swingbolts to be less than tool tight in the upright position.  Swingbolts were tightened and car was released to continue in transportation. On 7-17-15, local train crew reported the car had leaked from the top while being switched. Further inspection by the same contractor revealed six of fourteen bolts on the flanged and bolted manway of the combination housing were found to be less than tool tight.  Bolts were tightened which secured the car from further leakage.  Car was released to continue onto destination.
column169: Conduct proper pre and post inspection of car upon completion of loading or unloading, to ensure all valves, fittings and closures are in a closed and secure condition preventing release of liquid, vapor or gas while car is in transportation.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While at truckstop, leak was discovered inside trailer. Hanser's Wrecker Company was dispatched to assess. Upon inspection, it was determined that freight had shifted in transit, which resulted in the loss of approximately 8 gallons of free product. Product released to the trailer floor and adjacent freight, and was contained to an impervious surface. Dried product was recovered from trailer floor and containerized along with cleanup debris into poly bags. Waste was placed back on trailer, to be sent along with recovered freight. Product released was non-hazardous and did not cause threat to human health or environment. There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Roadrunner Transportation Services will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: At 1216 EST Conway notified ERTS of a release of UN1263 Deltron DMD 1683 Black Paint. The release was contained to the pallet and the box that the damaged can was in. The release was approximately 1 gallon from (1) 1-gallon container. Conway personnel performed clean up, breaking down the impacted materials and cardboard, (1) damaged pail, and (1) impacted pail. These items were placed into a 5-gallon over pack. The remaining pallet has been shrink wrapped. All items were labeled and placed into OS&D. No waterways, storm drains, or soils were reported to have been impacted by this release.

column168: THESE 2 PACKAGES (2ND TRACKING # IS 6400-3181-2597) WERE EXHIBITING A STRONG ODOR OF FUEL. ON THE INVOICES THE CONTENTS WERE DESCRIBED AS CELL ASSEMBLY FUEL SYSTEMS, EVALUATE AND QUOE PRIOR TO STARTING WORK, LEAKING FUEL. AS THE SHIPPER HAD NOT OFFERED THE PACKAGES WITH ANY DG MARKINGS, DG LABELS NOR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION, IT'S BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED OR HIDDEN DG.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING THEIR INVESTIGATION.

column168: The shipment was found leaking in the sort. The spill was recovered and the remaining contents were placed in-a salvage bag & salvage drum.  Upon opening the box we found two four liter broken brown glass jars. There were plastic pillows surrounding the jars. The shipper provided the package test repoort that calls for a Polystyrene upper and lower stabilizer, yet no mention of plastic pillows. There was no barrier bag or absorbent material present. The shipper subsequently sent a video showing Dichloromethane destroying the Polystyrene during a test. Based on my experience I believed the shipment to be improperly packaged. I notified the FAA, I spoke to Hazmat Manager David Schaufler, The freight was held for an FAA inspection.

column168: EMPLOYEE WAS LOADING IN A TRAILER WHEN HE FELT A BURNING SENSATION ON HIS LEFT ANKLE. HE NOTICED THERE WAS A YELLOW STAIN ON HIS SOCK. UPON REMOVING THE SOCK HE OBSERVED IT BEGIN TO SMOKE, AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR, WHO SENT HIM TO THE SAFETY OFFICE. THE SUPERVISOR INSPECTED THE TRAILER AND NOTICED A HAZMAT PACKAGE THAT APPEARED WET, AND NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER APPROACHED THE PACKAGE WEARING MINIMUM PPE, AND NOTED SHIPPING PAPERS THAT INDICATED THE CONTENTS WERE NITRIC ACID, WITH DIAMOND HAZARD LABELS OF CORROSIVE 8 AND OXIDIZER 5.2. AT THIS POINT HE NOTICED THAT THE PACKAGE HAD BEGUN GENERATING VISIBLE FUMES, AND NOTIFIED HIS RMP. THE RMP INSTRUCTED HIM TO CORDON OFF THE AREA, THEN ACTIVATED THE CHAIN OF COMMAND AND NOTIFIED THE DISTRICT SPILL COORDINATOR, WHO CALLED FOR AN OUTSIDE RESPONSE TEAM. IN ORDER TO PREVENT THE FUMES FROM ENTERING INTO THE HUB, THE TRAILER WAS PULLED OFF THE WALL INTO THE YARD TO AWAY TO OUTSIDE RESPONDERS, WHO DISPOSED OF THE PACKAGE.
column169: THE PACKAGE MAY HAVE FALLEN OFF THE EXTENDO, RESULTING IN THE INNER PACKAGING SHATTERING. A MORE IMPACT RESISTANT INNER PACKAGING COULD HELP PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS. KEEPING SIMILAR HAZMAT PACKAGES OFF THE BELTS AND TRANSPORTING THEM TO THEIR DESTINATIONS WITHIN THE HUB VIA BULK CART COULD ALSO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS.

On July 20, 2015, at 23:25 hours, Mechanical Foreman at the CSXT Parkersburg Yard, Parkersburg, West Virginia reported that GATX 72773, a residue tank car of UN1789, Hydrochloric Acid. Reportedly, there was a slight vapor cloud being emitted from the top of the tank car intermittently. The tank car was isolated. The shipper, Tetra Technologies Inc. was notified directly and Ron Anderson, (304) 488-5419 responded to inspect and secure the release. Ron Anderson found that the release was from the fill hole and after tightening the fill hole bolts further the release of vapor stopped.     This incident did require a special move.  NARRI: 5x(4+5+0)x(2+0) = 90  Cause code:224

column168: During a routine pre trip vehicle inspection a Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. driver discovered a leaking container on a van load containing hazardous waste. The driver contacted his dispatcher to report the release. A response crew was notified and summoned to the scene, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the truck and unloaded the leaking cubic yard container. The cubic yard container was repacked into drums for continued transportation to the final disposal facility. The trailer floor was cleaned with a and returned to service. The release was reported to the Wyoming Department of Environmental Quality. Online submittal system provided report #150803-1128.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or breakage was observed. This release was the direct result of improper container selection and preparation. The driver will be retrained on proper container selection for solid and liquid waste streams. The shipper was notified and advised to use an appropriate UN rated container for future shipment of this waste stream.

column168: On 07/27/15 at 8:45 AM, a loader was in the process of setting railcar GATX 1028 which contained 50% peroxide. This was for the second half of a split load. The loader removed all 4 bolts from the product outlet flange on the top of the railcar. The flange was stuck on the product outlet so the loader used the wrench to pry it open.  The flange came loose and product immediately started flowing out of the product outlet. The peroxide sprayed the loader while he was coming down the railcar ladder. A fellow employee guided him to the safety shower and he began to remove his chemical suit and flush his eyes for approximately 15-20 minutes.  The loader felt some irritation in his left eye.  The loader was then taken to the emergency room for additional care. He was released from the hospital a short while later and followed up with a visit to Arrow’s medical clinic. There was no damage to his eye and was released to work with no restrictions. The terminal manager contacted Chemtrec, TRANSFLO, and the Arrow upper management. The manager also filed a report with the NRC. The report number is 1123937.        The railcar continued to spray product for about 20 minutes and then continued to bubble out until 10:30 AM. One of the loaders who responded to the spill hooked up the 2 inch water hose to the fire hydrant and flushed the railcar and the surrounding area until the product stopped flowing from the railcar. The AMS loader flushed the released material from 9:00 to 9:30am.  The fire department and police department arrived around 9:30 AM. The fire department hooked up the fire hydrant outside the front gate and closed the entrance to the terminal off for about 2 hours. They flushed the railcar for about ten minutes (from 10:20 – 10:30). The Fire Department then put on chemicals suits, climbed the railcar, and opened the dome lid to relieve the rest of the excess pressure. The Fire Department left shortly after. Hepaco arrived around 11:00  A.M. to dilute and clean up the peroxide. The peroxide and water puddled up by the drain since the drain valve was closed.  At appx 1:50pm the Philadelphia Water Department gave approval to open the storm drain and further dilute the remaining peroxide.  Prior to opening the drain, the liquid on the ground was tested by Arcadis and was 12% peroxide.      At appx. 1:50pm PWD advised the terminal to slowly open the drain valve while continuing to flush and measure concentrations until the concentration reached 0%, at which time they were to continue to flush with water for an additional 3 hours.    Hepaco flushed the area with water with a 1.5 inch hose for 4 hours and completed the job around 6:00 P.M.     The product remaining in the railcar was measured at 32 inches of outage. Arkema estimated that 1580 gallons of peroxide was released.
column169: 1. A stand down was held with the entire staff on 07/28/15 from Marc Scena at TRANSFLO.  2. A stand down was held with the entire staff on 07/30/15 from Mike DiNapoli and Philip Crouthamel.  3. On 07/28/15, all employees that load peroxide were instructed that all peroxide railcars need vented by opening the manway.   4. The entire Arrow Network had a safety standdown on 8/12 to discuss the importance of safety and following work instructions  5. Management will spot audit peroxide loads for compliance with the work instructions  6. The loader received documented performance coaching on 8/6

column168: On July 24, 2015 at 0640 EST, a CMTV was backing up during the process of loading without closing the dome lid and approximately six (6) gallons was splashed out and was released to the concrete surface of the Kinder Morgan terminal bay floor. The duration of the release was basically instantaneously. The driver upon discovery contacted Skytank QDI headquarters at 0710 EST and notified of this cargo release and a hazardous materials emergency response contractor was dispatched with an estimated 60 minute response time and the spilled materials were containerized and the impervious surfaces were vacuumed and pressure washed and completed mitigation by 1402 ESt on July 24, 2015.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, TYPE A PACKAGE NON-SPECIAL FORM, NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: A low-level radioactive source (Tantalum 182, source), properly contained in a DOT Type 7A, labelled and locked container, was inadvertently received by provided by Nacher Corporation (Nacher) on 7/28/2015.  The source was offered by Tracerco to BHP Billiton Petroleum (GOM) Inc.'s (BHPB) for shipment on BHPB's Shenzi TLP located in the Gulf of Mexico.  Nacher notified BHPB of receiving the package on 7/28/2015, and BHPB began an investigation after being notified of the event. At this time, the incident remains under investigation.  Upon completion of the investigation, BHPB will submit a supplemental report containing the sequence of events and recommendations or actions to prevent recurrence.
column169: At this time, the incident remains under investigation.  Upon completion of the investigation, BHPB will submit a supplemental report containing the sequence of events and recommendations or actions to prevent recurrence.

Driver arrived at Eco Services in Baton Rouge and operator was doing an inspection of the trailer before letting him enter the plant and noticed a slight drip coming from the flange in between the internal and external valves. The operator had the driver put spill pads under the drip and he then notified dispatch of the leak.    OMI Repair facility was called out with a mechanic from our Baton Rouge terminal. The flange bolts between the internal and external valve were loose which caused a very slow drip from that flange from residual material in the line from loading through the outlet piping. The bolts were tightened and the leak was stopped. The customer inspected the trailer to make sure the problem was corrected and then allowed the trailer into their facility for offloading. The cargo was off loaded without incident.

column168: THE INCIDENT OCCURRED BETWEEN 21:30 AND 22:00 HOURS WHEN OUR DRIVER (GEORGE HOSFELD) WAS ON SITE TO DELIVER GASOLINE INTO UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS FOR SPEEDWAY 6768. WHEN THE DRIVER WAS READY TO UNLOAD THE PREMIUM GASOLINE FROM THE TRAILER HE PULLED TWO HOSES FROM THE TRAILER AND LAID THEM SIDE BY SIDE. HE FIRST CONNECTED THE FITTING TO THE TANK AND THEN ONE OF THE TWO HOSES. WHEN HE RETURNED TO THE TRAILER HE PICKED UP THE WRONG HOSE END AND CONNECTED TO THE TRAILER.  WITHOUT REVIEWING HIS STEPS AND CHECKING THAT HE HAD CONNECTED THE CORRECT HOSE HE OPENED THE VALVE ALLOWING THE GASOLINE TO FLOW. HE IMMEDIATELY REALIZED HIS ERROR WHEN GASOLINE CAME OUT OF THE HOSE AND SHUT THE TRAILER VALVE OFF. THE TIME IT WAS OPEN WAS APPROXIMATELY THREE TO FIVE SECONDS ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 15 TO 30 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO ESCAPE FROM THE HOSE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY BEGIN USING PADS, SOCKS AND ABSORBENT TO COLLECT THE PRODUCT. UNFORTUNATELY THE GASOLINE TRAVELED FURTHER THAN HE COULD RESPOND TO AND ENTERED THE PARKING LOT STORM WATER RUNOFF. WHERE THE GASOLINE WAS SPILLED AT THE FILLS AND TO THE STORM WATER RUNOFF IS CEMENT & ASPHALT. THE RUNOFF RUNS ACROSS ONE ENTRANCE/EXIT, UNDER THE LANDSCAPING AND INTO ANOTHER STORM WATER RUNOFF AT THE OTHER ENTRANCE/EXIT.  THE STORM WATER RUNOFF EVENTUALLY EMPTIES INTO A DRY COLLECTION POINT FOR STORM WATER.  THE COLLECTION AREA IS DIRT, GRASS AND STONE. THE STORM WATER RUNOFF CONSISTS OF CONCRETE AND PIPE. THE CONCRETE PORTION IS OPEN AND COVERED WITH A METAL GRATE TO ALLOW VEHICLES TO PASS OVER. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ALERTED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. ON ARRIVAL THEY WERE ABLE TO ASSIST AND ADVISED THAT DUE TO DEBRIS IN THE DRAINS THAT NONE OF THE GAS WAS ABLE TO REACH THE CONTAINMENT AREA AND THAT IT HAD NOT ENTERED ANY SEWERS, WATERWAYS OR SOIL. AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED (HEPACO, CONTACT: KARL HEEBNER, PH:215.739.3224) WHICH RESPONDED TO THE SCENE IN APPROXIMATELY 1HR. 30MINS. ON THE SCENE THEY CLEANED THE CONCRETE/ASPHALT AREA, CLEANED THE DEBRIS AND GASOLINE FROM THE STORM WATER RUNOFF & JETTED THE PIPE THAT TRAVELS UNDER THE LANDSCAPE. ALL WASTE WAS DRUMMED FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: On July 9, 2015 at approximately 8:15am, Heritage Transport, LLC driver contaced the compliance manager at Heritage Environmental Services, LLC in Kansas City to respond to a leaking 55 gallon container on Heritage Transport Van located at Butler Transport in Kansas City, KS.  Heritage Environmental contacted Haz-Mat Response, an emergency response service provider at approximately 8:30am to initiate a response to the spill and assist with clean-up.  At approximately 9:00am, Heritage representatives met with Haz-Mat Response, Inc. at Butler Transport, Inc. and conducted an initial site assessment and coordinated the response effort.  Based on the initial assessment, the 55 gallon container had inadvertently shifted forward in the trailer and leaked approximately 2/3 of it contents onto the trailer floor and exited the trailer and drained onto the asphalt pavement and soil adjacent to the pavement.    At 10:00am, the responding crew members of Haz-Mat arrived on-site and the Site Safety Plan was reviewed.  Haz-Mat Response crew neutralized the spilled material on the exterior of the trailer with a soda ash and water solution.  Clay absobent was then used to absorb the spilled material and neutralizing solution inside the trailer and on the ground.  Spill clean-up materials were placed into two 55 gallon containers, labeled and transported back to Heritage Environmental Services in Kansas City, Missouri.  After completing the initial site assessment and initiating response activities, the National Response Center and the Kansas Department of Health and Environment were notified by telephone.    The trailer arrived at the Heritage Environmental Services, LLC, Kansas City Missouri facility at approximately 11:45am, where an additional assessment and  inspection of the trailer and  its contents.  At approximately 1:00pm, the safety plan was reviewed with Heritage personnel.  Contaminated pallets were removed from the trailer and placed onto plastic liners inside the Heritage Storage Building.  Heritage personnel further neutralized the impacted wood pallets with a baking soda and water solution.  The pallets were allowed to dry and then placed onto an enddump destined for thermal destruction.  Spill response residues consisting of  clay absorbent, plastic liners, used personal protective equipment and visually impacted surface soil was placed into a 55-gallon plastic container and labeled.    Materials Involved in Incident    The container  was identified to be Line 7 of manifest 000655210WAS, UN3264, Waste Corrosive Liquid, Acidic, Inorganic, N.O.S., 8, PGII, (Nitric Acid, Ammonium Fluoride), (D011 D007), ERG#154.  Attachment A provides a copy of the Uniform Hazardous Waste Manifest, Land Disposal Restriction notice, and internal transportation documents used by Heritage Transport, LLC for the consignment.  Approximately 30 gallons ( 300 Pounds) spilled from the container.    Root Cause Analysis and Corrective Actions  The 55 gallon container that sh

column168: DRIVER WAS GIVEN A WRONG TANK CHART BY CUBBY’S STATION. HE MISCALCULATED THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THAT WOULD FIT IN THE TANK IN PART FROM THE BAD TANK CHART. HE BEGAN OFF LOADING AND THE UNDERGROUND TANK OVERFLOW FAILED AND RAN THE TANK OVER. THE DRIVER DID NOT LOCK THE CAR LOCKS ON THE VAPOR RETURN HOSE AND BACKFILLING PRODUCT KNOCKED IT OFF CAUSING PRODUCT TO SPILL FROM IT. THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN PUMPS AND NOTIFIED HIS TERMINAL WHO THEN CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND CLEAN UP.

column168: OUR DRIVER, HAULING A TANKER CONTAINING HOT ASPHALT, WAS EXITING THE HIGHWAY ON A OFF RAMP. HE WAS DRIVING TOO FAST AND WHEN HE HIT THE CURVE IN THE ROAD, HE LOST CONTROL AND THE TANKER ROLLED OVER. WHEN IT LANDED ON ITS SIDE THE DOME LID ON TOP WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED AND BEGAN TO LEAK. APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS LEAKED OUT AND ONTO THE ROADWAY. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. WAS ABLE TO SECURE THE LID CLOSED WITH SOME 4X4 WOOD PIECES AND A RATCHET STRAP. THERE WERE NO CRACKS OR HOLES IN THE TANKER, AS SOON AS THE LID WAS SECURED THE LEAK HAD STOPPED.
column169: DRIVERS OBEYING SPEED LIMITS AND BEING EXTRA CAREFUL AROUND TURNS BECAUSE WHEN DRIVING WITH A LARGE ABOUT OF LIQUID IN A TANKER IT CAN CAUSE THE MATERIAL TO SHIFT AND THROW THE WEIGHT OF THE VEHICLE TO ONE SIDE CAUSING A ROLL OVER. ALSO PROPERLY SECURING THE DOME LID SO THAT IT IS AS TIGHT AS POSSIBLE, INSTEAD OF JUST TIGHT ENOUGH TO CLOSE THE LID.

column168: OWNER OPERATOR CLAIMS HE WAS CUT OFF AFTER GOING THROUGH ROUND-A-BOUT IN CENTER OF TOWN. RATHER THAN HIT THE VEHICLE THAT CUT HIM OFF, HE TRIED TO SWERVE TO THE RIGHT. DRIVER HIT INDUSTRIAL DUMPSTER PLACED IN ROADWAY. DISCHARGE VALVE WAS AREA OF TRAILER THAT HIT THE DUMPSTER. NO PENETRATION TO THE INTERNAL TANKS. LOSS OF PRODUCT WAS WHAT WAS CONTAINED IN DISCHARGE VALVE AND PIPING.
column169: FOCUSING ON TRAINING INVOLVING SITUATIONAL AWARENESS AND ACCIDENT AVOIDANCE.

column168: R/P CONTACT PERS TO REPORT A DIESEL FUEL SPILL FROM A OVERTURNED CARGO TANK MOTOR VEHICLE. R/P STATED THE INVOLVED COMPANY NAME IS “RELADYNE”. HOWEVER, NO SEARCH RESULT WAS FOUND FOR THAT COMPANY. THE COMPANY ADDRESS GIVEN MATCHED TO PUMPELLY OIL INC. CUSTOMER #1847. EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL AND LAW ENFORCEMENT ARE ON SCENE. THE CARGO TANK WAS LOADED WITH APPROXIMATELY 3,800 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL. THE QUANTITY  RELEASED IS UNDERMINED. THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT IS UNDETERMINED. A CLEANUP COMPANY WAS DISPATCHED BY THE COMPANY OR RESPONSE PERSONNEL.  PERS MADE THIRD=PARTY REPORTS TO THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS HOTLINE AT 877-925-6595 (LA INCIDENT REPORTS #15-02727); BEAUREGARD PARISH LEPC AT 337046303281 (REPORTED TO: DEPUTY CHEEVER); AND TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AT 800-424-8802 (NRC REPORTS #1121981)
column169: THE ACTIONS TAKEN ARE MORE TRAINING IN SAFE DRIVING PRACTICES, SITUATIONAL AWARENESS, AND DISTRACTED DRIVING.

column168: A TANKER TRANSPORTING 7,939 GALLONS OF DENATURED ETHANOL WAS TURNING FROM I-70 WESTBOUND ONTO I-270 SOUTHBOUND, WEST OF COLUMBUS, OHIO, WHEN IT OVERTURNED AND STRUCK THE OVERPASS BRIDGE SUPPORT FOR I-70 EASTBOUND AS IT OVERTURNED. THE TANKER IGNITED AND BURNED FOR NEARLY 2.5 HOURS, DAMAGING THE BRIDGE OVERPASS SUPPORT. SPILLED ETHANOL MIXED WITH LIQUID FIRE SUPPRESSANT AND WATER FLOWED BEHIND A CONCRETE BARRIER AND INTO A DRAINAGE-WAY. A PRIVATE CLEANUP CONTRACTOR FLUSHED PRODUCT FROM BEHIND THE CONCRETE BARRIER. ALL STANDING LIQUID (6,400 GALLONS) WAS VACUUMED AND REMOVED OFF-SITE FOR DISPOSAL. THE OHIO EPA SUPERVISED EXCAVATION OF 11.85 TONS OF SOIL FROM THE DRAINAGE-WAY, WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED OFF-SITE FOR DISPOSAL.  A GEOLOGIST INSPECTED THE EXCAVATION USING HIS PID, BUT SOILS WERE ALL 0.0 PPM.  THE OHIO EPA APPROVED BACKFILL AND SITE RESTORATION, WHICH WAS PERFORMED AND A 30 DAY REPORT WAS SUBMITTED TO THE OHIO EPA FOR CLOSURE.THE DAMAGED OVERPASS BRIDGE AND SUPPORTS WERE REPLACED.
column169: HOC TRANSPORT WAS PROVIDED INSTRUCTIONS TO THEIR DRIVERS TO TAKE BETTER PRECAUTIONS WHEN HANDLING TANKERS, ESPECIALLY AROUND CORNERS. IT IS RECOMMENDED THAT ALL TANKERS USING THIS INTERCHANGE MAINTAIN CAUTION.

column168: ON SUNDAY, JULY 12, 2015 AT APPROXIMATELY 6:45 AM, TRANSPORT DRIVER MICHAEL GADSON WAS TRAVELING EAST ON HIGHWAY 82 BEWEEN ALBANY, GA AND SYLVESTER GA. WHEN HIS UNIT DRIFTED ONTO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. AS THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO RETURN TO THE HIGHWAY, THE UNIT ROLLED OVER. THE TANK SIDES RUPTURED AND PRODUCT BEGAN TO SPILL IN THE DITCH. EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREWS USED DIRT/SAND TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. IT IS UNKNOWN AS TO THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE.
column169: THE INTERCOMPANY SAFETY REVIEW BOARD FOUND THE DRIVER WAS AT FAULT IN THE ACCIDENT. HE WAS THEN TERMINATED. FUEL SOUTH EXPRESS WILL CONTINUE TO HOLD REGULARLY SCHEDULED SAFETY TRAINING MEETINGS WITH ALL THE DRIVERS. IN OUR NEXT MEETING, WE WILL EMPHASIZE THE DANGERS OF A ROLLOVER INCIDENT. FUEL SOUTH EXPRESS HAS PREVIOUSLY TRAINED ON THIS TOPIC AND IS COMMITTED TO THE CONTINUATION OF THAT TRAINING. WE WILL CONTINUE TO EMPHASIZE PROPER MAINTENANCE TO INSURE OUR EQUIPMENT IS OPERATING PROPERLY. WE REVIEW QUALCOMM REPORTS REGULARLY TO MONITOR DRIVER SPEED AND AMOUNT OF TIME OFF DUTY. DIRVER TRAINING HAS BEEN AND WILL CONTINUE TO BE OF THE UPMOST IMPORTANCE OF OUR COMPANY.

column168: MATERIAL WITH A SIGNIFICANT PERCENTAGE OF LIQUID WAS LOADED INTO LINED CUBIC YARD BOXES BY CHROME TECH, THESE BOXES WERE THEN SEALED AND BANDED TO SKIDS. ADVANCED WASTE CARRIERS PICKED UP THE LOAD OF 6 CUBIC YARD BOXES FORM CHROME TECH IN FRANKLIN, WI AND TRANSPORTED THEM TO ADVANCED WASTE SERVICES OF PA 10 DAY TRANSFER FACILITY IN NEW CASTLE, PA FOR FINAL DELIVERY INTO INMETCO LOCATED IN ELLWOOD CITY, PA.  DURING THE TRANSITION OF THE CUBIC YARD BOXES INTO THE 10 DAY STORAGE ONE OF THE BOXES WHEN NO LONGER SUPPORTED BY OTHER BOXES AND SIDE WALL OF THE TRUCK SPILLED A PORTION OF ITS CONTENTS INTO THE TRUCK AND ONTO THE PAVEMENT OF THE PARKING LOT.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED BY THE IMMEDIATE PLACEMENT OF A CONTAINMENT DIKE OF ABSORBENT, SPILL BOOMS, AND SPILL PADS.  THERE WAS A SIGNIFICANT RAIN THAT OCCURRED AT THE SAME TIME.  THE SPILLED LIQUID AND CONTAMINATED RAIN WATER WAS PUMPED INTO DRUMS RESULTING IN 2 DRUMS OF LIQUID, THE ABSORBENT WAS ALSO PLACED INTO DRUMS RESULTING IN 5 DRUMS OF SOLIDS.  DUE TO CONCERNS REGARDING CONTAINER INTEGRITY ALL 6 CUBIC YARD BOXES WERE TRANSFERRED INTO A HAZARD RATED LINED ROLL-OFF BOX FOR DELIVERY INTO INMETCO THE FOLLOWING DAY JULY 10 2015. THE DRUMS OF SPILL CLEAN UP WASTE WERE SENT TO AES ENVIRONMENTAL ON MANIFEST 012156601JJK

column168: DRIVER WAS HEADING WESTBOUND ON HIGHWAY 70 NEAR WAURIKA, OK AND APPARENTLY FELL ASLEEP. HE RAN OFF THE ROAD ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY, AND ROLLED OVER THE TRACTOR/TANKER TRAILER. COMPARTMENT #1 OF THE TANKER TRAILER CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 3,000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE, AND WAS PUNCTURED BY THE ROLLOVER ACCIDENT. THE GASOLINE SPILLED OUT OF THE TANKER INTO A FIELD. SOME OF IT RAN DOWN HILL INTO A FARM POND. THE RELEASE PROBABLY TOOK 1-2 HOURS TO DRAIN OUT OF COMPARTMENT #1 ON TO THE GROUND. EMS/FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO ACCIDENT SCENE. HULL ENVIRONMENTAL WAS ALSO DISPATCHED TO ACCIDENT SCENE FOR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL CLEANUP AND REMEDIATION.
column169: WE ARE RE-TRAINING ALL DRIVERS ON TANKER ROLLOVER PREVENTION TECHNIQUES AND THE IMPORTANCE OF GETTING THEIR REQUIRED REST WHEN OFF DUTY. WE INSTRUCTED THE DRIVERS THAT IF THEY ARE TOO TIRED OR SICK TO DRIVE, THEY NEED TO CALL THEIR SUPERVISOR AND TAKE A SICK LEAVE DAY.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. TANK ROLL-OVER RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 100 LIQUID BARRELS OF PETROLEUM OIL. THE FREE LIQUID IMPACTED A SWALE ADJACENT TO HIGHWAY 1025 AND LINDER ROAD AND ALSO IMPACTED A NEARBY POND. UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE, LLC (USES) WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.     USES DEPLOYED ABSORBENT BOOMS IN THE IMPACTED POND AND EXCAVATED THE CONTAMINATED SOILS FROM THE IMPACT SWALE. USES UTILIZED A VACUUM TRUCK TO RECOVER CONTAMINATED WATER FROM THE DITCH LINE. SITE CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED ON AUGUST 7, 2015. USES COORDINATED DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS ACCIDENTAL, NO PLANS CURRENTLY EXIST TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. HOWEVER, GENESIS CRUDE OIL, L.P. WILL CONTINUE TO REINFORCE SAFETY GUIDELINES AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: THIS WAS NOT A PACKAGE FAILURE. THIS WAS AN AUTOMOBILE ACCIDENT. THE DRIVE HAD JUST PICKUP A LOAD OF DIESEL FUEL AT MAGELLAN TERMINAL 85 EAST ST NEW HAVEN CT 06511. HE THEN PROCEEDED TO RETURN BACK TO OFFICE AT 125 ATWATER ST PLANTSVILLE CT 06179. HE WAS TRAVELING ON I91N WHEN HIS FRONT TIRE BLEW OUT TRUCK WENT INTO GUARD RAILS, SPUN AROUND HIT BRIDGE PILLAR AND TANK BROKE OFF TRUCK. THE DIESEL FUEL CAME OUT ONTO HIGHWAY. RESPONSE FRO DOT, DEEP, STATE POLICE, LOCAL POLICE, FIRE AND AMBULANCE WAS ALMOST IMMEDIATELY. HIGHWAY CLOSED. DIESEL FUEL WAS BURNED OFF HIGHWAY. DOT PROCEEDED CLEAN UP. MCVAC ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED INTO CLEAN UP.

column168: THE INCIDENT INVOLVED A EQUIPMENT SERVICE TRUCK DESIGNED TO FUEL AND LUBRICATE CONSTRUCTION EQUIPMENT FOR JMAC RESOURCE, INC. THE UNIT TRAVELS FROM CONSTRUCTION SITE TO CONSTRUCTION SITE FOR JMAC TO COMPLETE IT WORKS. EQUIPMENT FUEL IS LOADED ONTO THE TRUCK IN JMAC’S YARD DAILY. IN THE DAYS BEFORE THE INCIDENT, THE DRIVE-SHAFT WAS REMOVED FROM THE VEHICLE TO ALLOW ACCESS TO REPAIR SOME STRUCTURAL COMPONENTS OF THE SERVICE BODY. THIS WORK WAS COMPLETED BY A THIRD PARTY WELDING SHOP, NOT AFFILIATED WITH JMAC RESOURCES. WHEN THE DRIVER-SHAFT WAS RE-INSTALLED THE THIRD PARTY VENDOR, FAILED TO INSTALL THREADLOCK ON THE BOLTS HOLDING THE U-JOINT TOGETHER AND DID NOT INFORM JMAC OF THIS FAILURE.     WHILE TRAVELING ON HIGHWAY 1804 NEAR EAST DAKOTA PARKWAY IN WILLSTON ND, THE BOLTS CAME OUT OF THE YOKE AND THE U-JOINT CAME APART. THE SPINNING DRIVE SHAFT THEN WHIPPED AROUND RESULTING IN THE BREAKAGE OF THE RAPID RELEASE CHECK VALVE OFF THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK, ALLOWING THE REMAINING CONTENTS (430 GALLONS) OF THE TANK TO EMPTY ONTO THE STREET. THE THREADED END OF THE THREE INCH VALVE THAT WAS THREADED INTO THE TANK BROKE. THE ENTIRE DURATION OF THE LEAK OCCURRED IN APPROXIMATELY 5 MINUTES.   DESPITE A RAPID RESPONSE TO THE INCIDENT BY WILLISTON FD AND THE DRIVER DEPLOYING HIS SPILL KIT, SOME FUEL WAS RELEASED INTO THE STORM SEWER. JMAC’S SPILL RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED SHORTLY THEREAFTER AND PLACED BOOMS AND PADS AT THE OUTLET OF THE STORM DRAIN AND BELIEVE IT CAPTURED THE FUEL PRIOR TO ENTERING ANY WATER BODY. MOST OF THE FUEL WAS RECAPTURED USING JMAC VAC TRUCKS TO REMOVE FUEL FROM THE ROAD AND SKIM FUEL FROM THE STORM SEWER. IT WAS THEN PROCESSED TO CLEANUP FOR SALE FOR RE-FINING. SOME MINOR ABSORBENT MATERIALS, BOOMS AND PADS WERE USED TO CLEAN THE PAVEMENT AND WERE DISPOSED OF IN THE NEARBY SMALL VOLUME INDUSTRIAL WASTE LANDFILL (IHD SOLIDS MANAGEMENT). THE STORM SEWER WAS PRESSURE WASHED. BOOMS REMAINED IN PLACE FOR A FEW WEEKS AFTER THE INCIDENT.
column169: THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE FAILURE BY THE WELDER TO RECOGNIZE THE NEED FOR THREADLOCK ON THE U-JOINT BOLTS. HAD A MECHANIC, FAMILIAR WITH PROPER PROCEDURES FOR THE DRIVELINE COMPLETED THE WORK, THE INCIDENT WOULD NOT HAVE OCCURRED. THE THIRD PART VENDOR WAS ADMONISHED FOR THIS FAILURE.   THE BODY MANUFACTURER COULD HAVE INSTALLED A GUARD OVER THE DRIVELINE THAT MAY HAVE PREVENTED THE DRIVESHAFT FROM CONTACTING THE VALVE/PIPING. THIS MAY HAVE LIMITED THE VISUAL OBSERVATION OF THE TRUCK BODY HOWEVER AND LEAD TO A SIMILAR INCIDENT AS THE RESULT OF THE DAMAGE THAT WAS BEING REPAIRED THAT LEAD TO THE BOLTS BEING REMOVED IN THE FIRST PLACE.   A REQUIREMENT THAT THE RAPID RELEASE CHECK VALVE BE INTERNAL TO THE TANK MAY HAVE MINIMIZED THE SPILL.   THERE MAY HAVE BEEN SOME WARNING IN THE FORM OF VIBRATION PRIOR TO THE DRIVELINE FAILURE, HOWEVER THE TRUCK HAS AN AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION WHICH MAY HAVE OBSCURED ANY VIBRATION. SINCE THE BOLTS WOULD LIKELY HAVE APPEARED TIGHT DURING THE PRE AND POST TRIP INSPECTIONS, THE DRIVER WOULD NOT HAVE HAD ANY FURTHER WARNING OF THE IMPENDING INCIDENT.

column168: AFTER FILLING THE TANK, DRIVER PROCEEDED TO BLOW OUT THE LINE. column169: DRIVER SPRAYED DOWN THE OUTSIDE OF THE TANK WITH WATER, INTO CONTAINMENT.    ROOT CAUSE OF INCIDENT:    PROCEDURES- WE HAVE INSTRUCTED DRIVERS BOTH VERBALLY AND IN WRITTEN PROCEDURES TO N OT FILL PAST THE 7/8 MARK IN THE TANK GAUGE. DOING SO CAN LEAD TO SPLASHING OUT OF THE PRODUCT AS THE HOSE IS CLEARED. THAT IS WHAT OCCURRED HERE DUE TO OVERFILLING OF THE TANK BY NOT FOLLOWING WRITTEN FILL PROCEDURES.     RETRAIN DRIVER IN PROPER FILLING TO 7/8 FULL MARK ON TANK GAUGES.

column168: DRIVER NOTICED A LEAK ON THE HANDLE OF THE DRY-MATE FITTING ON THE TANK FILL LINE AS HE WAS CHECKING THE FILL HOSE. DRIVER WENT BACK TO GET A TOOL TO TIGHTEN THE NUT ON THE DRY-MATE HANDLE. HE DID NOT SHUT DOWN THE PRODUCT FLOW AT THIS TIME. DRIVER CAME BACK TO TIGHTEN THE HANDLE, RETURNED THE TOOL, CAME BACK TO CHECK THE TANK LEVEL. THE TANK IS NOT LINE OF SITE, AND HE NOTICED THE TANK OVERFLOWING. DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE PRODUCT FLOW. APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS WERE ON THE CONCRETE FLOOR AROUND THE STORAGE TANK. NO INJURIES AND AN ENVIRONMENTAL CREW FROM SET THAT WAS ON SITE ALREADY CLEANED UP THE SPILL AFTER NEUTRALIZING WITH A DRY ALKALI. DID NOT SHUT DOWN AT SIGN OF INITIAL LEAK, TANK NOT LINE OF SIGHT AND SMALL SO REALLY A TWO PERSON FILL SHOULD BE THE NORM HERE. TANK SHOULD BE PUT ON SAFETY HOLD UNTIL WE VERIFY A PROCEDURE MOVING FORWARD. DRIVER DISTRACTED WHILE FILLING TANK AND TRYING TO FIX LEAK WITHOUT SHUTTING DOWN.
column169: TRAINING- DRIVER DID NOT SHUT DOWN AT FIRST SIGN OF THE INITIAL LEAK.  PROCEDURES- TANK NOT LINE OF SIGHT AND SMALL SO NEEDS TO BE A TWO PERSON FILL WITH A CUSTOMER SPOTTER.

column168: A&R RECEIVED CAR UTLX958379 FROM CSXT ON JULY 22 IN FAYETTEVILLE. THE CAR WAS MOVED TO RIVER TERMINAL TO BE HELD FOR UNLOADING BY THE CONSIGNEE, PARKER GAS, ON JULY 23. ON JULY 27, AT 10:00AM, OUR TRAIN CREW DETECTED AN ODOR OF PROPANE WHILE SWITCHING ON A TRACK ADJACENT TO WHERE UTLX958379 WAS SETTING, TRACK 12. THE TRAIN CREW SECURED THE AREA AROUND THE CAR. THE FAYETTEVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE CONSIGNEE WERE CONTACTED. AFTER THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED, A&R SUPERVISORS DISCUSSED HOW TO PROCEED WITH REPRESENTATIVES OF PARKER GAS AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. IT WAS AGREED, THAT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WOULD PROTECT THE AREA AND PREPARE TO RESPOND TO ANY FIRE THAT MAY OCCUR, WHILE REPRESENTATIVES FROM PARKER GAS INSPECTED THE CAR FOR A LEAK. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LIQUID VALVE ON THE CAR WAS LEAKING DUE TO THE FACT THAT IT WAS NOT PROPERLY CLOSED AFTER LOADING. THE VALVE WAS SECURED PROPERLY AND THE LEAK STOPPED. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RELEASED THE SCENE AT 11:50AM.
column169: THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THE CIRCUMSTANCES SURROUNDING THE INCIDENT.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column43: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column62: Human Error; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation
column168: WE PICKED UP 3 SKIDS OF INDUSTRIAL BATTERIES AT A CUSTOMER’S LOCATION. THESE BATTERIES WERE BEING RETURNED FOR RECYCLING. THE CUSTOMER HAD BANDED AND SHRINK WRAPPED THE BATTERIES TO THE SKIDS, BUT IT WAS NOT SUFFICIENT IN HOLDING THE BATTERIES IN PLACE ANF THE BATTERIES TITLED FORWARD ON ONE OF THE SKIDS. ONCE THE BETTERIES TILTED, ACID LEAKED ONTO THE FLOOR, AND THE EXHAUST OF THE TRUCK. THE DRIVER PULLED OVER AT THE SCALES, AND CALLED OUR CHEMICAL EMERGENCY #800. A CLEAN-UP CREW WAS THEN SENT OUT TO ACCESS THE SPILL AND CLEAN UP THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.
column169: WE HAVE GONE OVER THE CORRECT WAY TO PREPARE THE INDUSTRIAL BATTERIES FOR SHIPMENT WITH OUR CUSTOMER. IF THEY ARE GOING TO CONTINUE TO SEND INDUSTRIAL BATTERIES IN FOR RECYCLING, WE EXPECT THEM TO BAND THE BATTERIES VERTICALLY AND HORIZONTALLY TO THE SKID, TO ENSURE THEY ARE UNABLE TO TILT FORWARD OR TO THE SIDE. OUR DRIVER HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED TO REFUSE ANY SHIPMENT THAT HAS NOT BEEN PROPERLY PREPARED FOR SHIPPING.
column172: Pallet, used only for battery reports when no other container given

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: AS A CONTRACTOR TO BATH IRON WORKS, GRIMMELS, REMOVES 55-GALLON METAL DRUMS OF STEEL SHOT FOR RECYCLING. UPON RECEIPT AT OUR FACILITY, THE DRUMS WERE DUMPED FROM THE ROLL-OFF. THE IMPACT OF UNLOADING CAUSED THE RUPTURE OF TWO (2) OF THE DRUMS AND DAMAGE TO TWO OTHERS. THIS CAUSED THE CONTENTS OF THE TWO RUPTURED DRUMS TO SPILL ONTO THE CONCRETE PROCESSING PAD. THE SPILL REVEALED THAT THE TWO DRUMS CONTAINED PAINT WASTE MATERIAL, WHICH WAS NOT KNOWN AT THE TIME OF UNLOADING. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY PLACED ABSORBENT BOOM AROUND THE SPILL, AND STOOD UP THE RUPTURED AND DAMAGED DRUMS. THE RELEASE WAS MINIMIZED DUE TO THE IMMEDIATE RESPONSE BY GRIMMELS PERSONNEL, AND WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE CONCRETE PAD AREA. A SPILL CLEANUP CONTRACTOR (CLEAN HARBORS) WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED BY BATH IRON WORKS. THE ENTIRE AREA WAS REMEDIATED AND ALL WASTE WAS REPACKAGED BY THE CONTRACTOR. THE CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED WITHIN HOURS AND ALL WASTE WAS REMOVED FROM THE SITE THE NEXT DAY BY THE CONTRACTOR TO A LICENSED DISPOSAL FACILITY.
column169: BIW CONDUCTED AN EXTENSIVE REVIEW OF DRUMMED WASTE HANDLING ACTIVITIES. NEW PROCESSES HAVE BEEN INSTITUTED REGARDING THE REVIEW AND LABELING OF DRUMMED WASTE CONTAINERS TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. EMPLOYEES AT BATH IRON WORKS HAVE CONDUCTED ADDITIONAL TRAINING AND SUPERVISOR OVERSIGHT TO PREVENT ANY DRUMS FROM LEAVING THE FACILITY BEFORE BEING CHECKED BY EMPLOYEES WITH DIRECT RESPONSIBILITY FOR WASTE CHARACTERIZATION. THE PROCESS CHANGES HAVE BEEN COMMUNICATED TO GRIMMELS PERSONNEL TO HELP ENSURE PROPER REVIEW PRIOR TO TRANSPORTATION.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Human Error
column168: EAST PENN LOGISTICS, LLC WAS PICKING UP A LOAD OF JUNK LEAD ACID BATTERIES AT THE JAMAICA BUS DEPOT IN JAMAICA, NY. THE BOX TRUCK WAS LOADED AND THE DRIVER PULLED OFF. WHILE DRIVING DOWN THE ROAD, THE DRIVER NOTICED SMOKE COMING FROM THE BOX AND PULLED OVER. WHEN HE OPENED THE DOOR TO THE BOX HE SAW FLAMES AND HE QUICKLY PUT OUT THE FIRE. HE IMMEDIATELY CALLED 911. THE LOCAL FIRE COMPANY SPRAYED DOWN THE BATTERIES SINCE THEY WERE STILL WARM. THE DRIVER GOT THE OK FROM BOTH THE FIRE COMPANY AND THE POLICE TO MOVE THE BOX TRUCK DOWN THE ROAD TO A NEARBY HOTEL PARKING LOT. EAST PENN MANUFACTURING CONTRACTED A LOCAL HAZ MAT TEAM TO HELP CLEAN UP THE DEBRIS AND PALLETIZE THE LOAD. THREE, 55 GALLON POLY DRUMS WERE USED TO PUT THE (6) DAMAGED BATTERIES. APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF ACID WAS RELEASED. THE RELEASED ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CONTAINERIZED IN (1) 55 GALLONS DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. THE 3 POLY DRUMS, WITH DAMAGED BATTERIES, AND THE REST OF THE LOAD, WERE TAKEN BACK TO EAST PENN MANUFACTURING CO. FOR RECYCLE IN OUR SECONDARY LEAD SMELTER. NO DAMAGE WAS DONE TO THE BOX TRUCK EXCEPT A FEW BURN MARKS ON THE INSIDE OF THE TRUCK.
column169: PROPER PACKAGING TECHNIQUES OF SPENT LEAD ACID BATTERIES HAVE BEEN REVIEWED WITH THE JAMAICA DEPOT.     PROPER PACKAGING INSTRUCTIONS WILL ASLO BE REVIEWED WITH THE EAST PENN LOGISTICS, LLC DRIVERS. THE DRIVERS WILL ALSO BE RETRAINED AS TO WHEN NOT TO ACCEPT A LOAD, IF PACKAGED INCORRECTLY.

column168: CARRIER'S DRIVER AT CONSIGNEE LOCATION AND AS CONSIGNEE'S FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS MOVING TOWARD ONE OF THE BOXED PALLETS, THE FORKLIFT ARMS WERE TOO HIGH CAUSING ONE OF THE GALLON JUGS OF PRODUCT TO BE PUNCTURED. PRODUCT IN THE AMOUNT OF 6 OUNCES WAS SPILLED ON THE SHIPPER-OWNED TRAILER'S FLOOR AND CONSIGNEE'S WAREHOUSE FLOOR. CARRIER'S DRIVER AND CONSIGNEE'S FORKLIFT OPERATOR USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL. WASTE WAS SWEPT UP AND CONSIGNEE DISPOSED. THE DELIVERY WAS COMPLETED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENCE. CLAIM #47109

column168: CARRIER WAS OFFLOADING AT A CONSIGNEE LOCATION AND A LEAK DEVELOPED DUE TO LOOSE HOSE FITTINGS CAUSING 1 QUART OF PRODUCT TO SPILL ONTO CONSIGNEE'S CONCRETE PAD. CARRIER WAS ABLE TO REPLACE AND TIGHTEN THE HOSE FITTINGS TO FINISH DELIVERY. CARRIER APPLIED ABSORBENT TO SPILLED PRODUCT THEN USED SHOVEL AND BROOM TO PICK IT UP. column168: CARRIER WAS AT THE CONSIGNEE LOCATION WHEN WHILE UNHOOKING HOSE AFTER OFFLOADING, AN EXCESS PRESSURE IN THE LINE CAUSED 5 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT TO SPRAY OUT ONTO THE GROUND AND THE CARRIER'S DRIVER. THE CARRIER DRIVER USED AN EMERGENCY WASH STATION. NO INJURY AND NO MEDICAL TREATMENT WERE SOUGHT. THE CARRIER AND CONSIGNEE CLEANED THE SPILLED PRODUCT FROM THE EXPOSED DIRT GROUND WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND SHOVELED INTO CONSIGNEE'S WASTE BARREL TO BE DISPOSED OF BY CONSIGNEE.     EVENT #47190.

column168: A SMALL CRACK DEVELOPED IN A WELD ON THE BLOW-OFF LINE AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID WAS RELEASED. THE MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED USING ABSORBENT PADS.

column168: The employee did not get the fill nozzle securely tightened and when he opened the nozzle the pressure blew it off the cylinder vale he was getting ready to fill. The propane sprayed the right leg and right side of waist and groin area. The employee was hospitalized for observation and discharged on 07/31/15. The employee sustained 1st and 2nd degree propane freeze burns. He has not returned to work.
column169: The employee will be trained on filling cylinders per the Ferrellway.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Driver was having problems with the pump on his truck, thinking it was clogged.  He used a hammer to tap the side of the pump to try and clear the clog.  He then cracked the bleeder valve on the top side of the pump (not the normal bleeder valves that should have been used) and that’s when the gallon of product came out it sprayed driver face under the face shield.  The operator who was unloading shut down the product flow and driver went into the chemical shower. The driver had on most of the PPE that we require but instead of wearing chemical goggles he was wearing safety glasses with side shields.  The plant nurse didn’t observe any redness or obvious signs of irritation and doesn't seem to think he needed immediate medical attention but suggested he wait awhile and if it’s still irritated, he could go to the clinic that they use.  Driver did go to the clinic and checked out ok.  He has been feeling fine since.
column169: In my tenure at Schneider (18 years) this is a first for our team.  This was a driver behavior / decision making issue.  We have brought him in and went through what we call PET (Performance Enhancement Training) that focuses on what what went wrong and why and what to do in the future.  ie - if he can't get product flowing by normal means he / she should be shutting down and contacting safety for support on what to do next.  Driver understands moving foward what needs to happen.  If something of this nature happens again he will be on a signed Commitment To Excellence agreement where his employment with Schneider will be severed if it happens again.  We may forgo the Commitment to Excellence and sever ties depending on the circumstances.

column168: The driver was unhooking his liquid hose. He did not verify that all the pressure was off his hose before uncoupling. A very small amount of liquid/vapor splashed on his chest and arm.
column169: Driver has been hauling NH3 for 13 years. Driver failed to verify all pressure was off of unloading hose before loosing coupler/fitting.

column168: CARRIER AT CONSIGNEE LOCATION TO OFFLOAD. CONSIGNEE OPENED THE EXTERNAL VALVE ON CARRIER'S TRAILER TO OBTAIN A SAMPLE, 1 CUP OF PRODUCT SPILLED OUT, SPLASHING THE CONSIGNEE EMPLOYEE'S ARM AND IMPACTING THE BELOW ASPHALT GROUND. CONSIGNEE EMPLOYEE RECEIVED ON SITE FIRST AID. PRODUCT THAT IMPACTED THE GROUND WAS CLEANED BY CONSIGNEE. OFFLOADING WAS POSTPONED.  CARRIER MECHANIC INSPECTED THE TRAILER VALVES AND FOUND THE HEAD GASKET ON THE INTERNAL VALVE TO BE FAULTY. THE GASKET WAS REPLACED. PRODUCT WAS DELIVERED TO THE CUSTOMER WITH NO FURTHER ISSUES.    EVENT # 47196
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED

column168: CARRIER DRIVER AT CONSIGNEE LOCATION AND WHILE CONSIGNEE EMPLOYEE WAS OFF-LOADING PRODUCT INTO THEIR TOTE, THEIR NOZZLE BROKE OFF OF THEIR HOSE ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SPILL FOR LESS THAN A MINUTE BEFORE CARRIER DRIVER STOPPED THE PROCESS.  THE 5 GALLON RELEASE AFFECTED THE ASPHALT GROUND BELOW AND CONSIGNEE EMPLOYEE WAS EXPOSED.  CONSIGNEE EMPLOYEE REPLACED WITH A NEW NOZZLE AND CONTINUED OFFLOADING WITH NO FUTURE INCIDENCE.  CONSIGNEE CLEANED THE SPILL FROM THEIR ASPHALT SURFACE.    EVENT # 46988
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED

column168: CARRIER COMPLETED OFF LOADING, CLOSED VALVE ON WALL, TRAILER AND BLEED OFF THE AIR ON TRAILER WITH VALVE, DISCONNECTED HOSE FROM WALL AND PRODUCT SPRAYED OUT ABOUT 1-2 GALLONS AND THE PRODUCT HIT THE METAL CAGE AREA CAUSING IT TO SPRAY BACK ON CARRIER AND CONSIGNEE EMPLOYEE IN THE FACE/NECK AREA.  CARRIER AND CONSIGNEE EMPLOYEE WENT AND WASHED OFF, TAKE FULL SHOWERS WITH SOAP AND CHANGED CLOTHS.  CONSIGNEE CLEANED SPILL WITH DRY PADS.  CONSIGNEE TOOK EMLOYEE WENT TO HOSPITAL TO BE CHECKED OUT AS PRECAUTION.  CARRIER DETERMINED THAT PRESSURE WAS STILL IN THE HOSE WHEN HE DISCONNECTED HOSE FROM TANK.    EVENT 47285

column168: PART VI (DOT FORM F 5800    ON JULY 25, 2015, A DRIVER FOR SAVANNAH TRANSPORT WAS INVOLVED IN A REAR END COLLISION WHICH LED TO THE SEQUENCE OF EVENTS THAT CAUSED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL.    OUR DRIVER WAS ON I-80 EAST BOUND MM 25, HE CAME UP ON ANOTHER TRUCK CARRYING LUMBER ON A FLAT BED SEMI TRAILER GOING APPX 20 MPH. OUR TRUCK WAS TRAVELING 70 MILES PER HOUR WHEN WE IMPACTED THE OTHER TRUCK AND TRAILER.     WE WERE CARRYING A LOAD OF HAZARDOUS WASTE DRUMS DESTINED FOR AES IN CALVERT CITY, KY. UPON IMPACT THE LOAD SHIFTED OUT OF THE NOSE AND SIDE OF OUR TRAILER ALLOWING THE DRUMS TO SPILL OUT ONTO THE ROADWAY. THE DRUM FAILURE WAS CAUSED BY THE BLUNT IMPACT OF THE ACCIDENT.   THE WYOMING HWY PATROL WAS FIRST ON SCENE, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ALSO RESPONDED. OUR DRIVER WAS KILLED UPON IMPACT. SAVANNAH TRANSPORT WAS CONTACT BY THE WYOMING HWY PATROL DISPATCH OFFICE. AN EMERGENCY RESPONDER FROM SALT LAKE CITY WAS SENT TO THE SCENE TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP PROCESS. THAT COMPANY’S NAME IS ENVIRO CARE OUT OF NORTH SALT LAKE, UTAH. THE ROAD CLEANUP AND MATERIAL WAS DONE BY AFTERNOON THAT SAME DAY.     THE MATERIAL FROM THE CLEAN UP WAS BROUGHT BACK TO SLC, UTAH IN ROLL OFF BINS AND HANDLED FROM THERE FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. THIS HAS BEEN QUITE THE PROCESS. ON AUGUST 6TH & 7TH A CREW FROM ENVIOR CARE WORKING WITH WYDOT DID REMEDIATION ON THE SITE OF THE ACCIDENT.
column169: PART VII (DOT FORM F 5800)   AS ALWAYS SAFETY COMES FIRST AT SAVANNAH TRANSPORT. THIS WAS A VERY UNFORTUNATE ACCIDENT. WE ARE ALWAYS STRIVING TO BE ACCIDENT FREE AND BASED ON OUR CA SCORES YOU CAN SEE HAT WE DO VERY WELL IN THIS AREA. THIS IS THE FIRST FATAL ACCIDENT IN THE HISTORY OF SAVANNAH TRANSPORT AND WE ARE VERY COMMITTED TO MAKE IT OUT LAST. IN THIS PARTICULAR EVENT, I DON’T THINK THERE WAS ANY DRUM FAILURE BY THE SHIPPER THAT WOULD COME INTO PLAY, THE DAMAGE AND RELEASE OF PRODUCT WAS CAUSE SOLELY BY THE ACCIDENT.
